, France":"Blois, Loir-et-Cher, France","Rouen, Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, France":"Rouen, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Angers","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Aime, Marcel, Pierre, Adelard, Aristide, Eudore, Fernand, Florent, Gilles, Henri, Jean-Paul, Jean-Yves.","French: habitational name from Angers in Maine-et-Loire, France, the capital of Anjou before the French Revolution. It was called in Latin <i>Andrecavis</i>, being the home of the Gaulish tribe known as the <i>Andrecavi</i> in Roman times."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Adelaide","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic origin (via French  <b>Adélaïde</b> ), from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>heid</i> ‘kind, sort’. It was borne in the 10th century by the wife of the Holy Roman Emperor Otto the Great. She became regent after his death and was revered as a saint. The given name increased in popularity in England during the 19th century, when it was borne by the wife of King William IV; she was the daughter of the ruler of the German duchy of Saxe-Meiningen. The Australian city of Adelaide was named in her honour."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Adelaide d' Angers was born on 5 August 1112. She had at least 1 son with Geoffrey Plantagenet Count of Anjou. She died on 10 September 1169, in Rouen, Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France, at the age of 57."},"et":{"5 August 1112–10 Sep 1169":"5. august 1112–10. september 1169","1113–1151":"1113–1151","1130–1202":"1130–1202","1112–1169":"1112–1169","5 August 1112":"5. august 1112","1169":"1169","1202":"1202","1113":"1113","1112":"1112","1130":"1130","7 September 1151":"7. september 1151","1151":"1151","about 1130":"umbes 1130","10 Sep 1169":"10. september 1169","Château-du-Loir, Sarthe, Pays de la Loire, France":"Château-du-Loir